In Kotlin you cannot instantiate a variable before the constructor but you can do something similar.

 1. 
 You can declare a variable without initialising it and then add its value to it in a function. This allows you to add its own functionality to it.
For example:

    class one {
      lateinit var variable1: String
      
      constructor(){}
      
      fun play() {
        variable1 = &quot;one&quot;
      }
    }

 2. 
You can declare the variable with a null and then assign a value to it in the constructor. 
For example:

    class two(val parameter: Int) {
        var two: String? = null
    
        init {
            two= &quot;two&quot;
        }
    }

Just to be clear about what we&#39;re talking about, in your Java example, the member variables are getting initialized here:

```java
public class Cat1 {
    String name = &quot;Name&quot;;

    public Cat1() {
        // super(); &lt;-- Implicit when you omit it
        // name gets initialized at this point of time during constructor call.
        System.out.println(name); 
    }
}
```

So it&#39;s not initialized before the constructor, but it&#39;s initialized immediately following the super-constructor call.

In Kotlin, you have both property initializations and `init` blocks that are called *after* the initialization of any properties in the *primary* constructor, but before the code in the blocks of any *secondary* constructors.

Property initializations and `init` blocks are called in order from top to bottom.

So the simplest way to duplicate your class example is to use a primary constructor and an `init` block after your property:
```kotlin
public class Cat1() { 
    var name: String = &quot;Name&quot;

    init {
        println(name)
    }
}
```
Note, parentheses for the primary constructor are optional if it has no parameters and there are no secondary constructors.

If you have a secondary constructor, your properties will initialized before its block of code:

```kotlin
public class Cat1 { 
    var name: String = &quot;Name&quot;

    constructor() {
        println(name)
    }
}
```
...even if they are declared later (just like in Java):
```kotlin
public class Cat1 { 
    constructor() {
        println(name)
    }

    var name: String = &quot;Name&quot;
}
```

